  "notes": "ANTI-OVERCLAIM: this packet proves only an infrastructure sublemma used toward the integer_isGoodPair_iff characterization, which itself is a companion/partial result for Erdos #349's INTEGER case -- it does not resolve Erdos #349's general open question (for which real t, alpha is floor(t*alpha^n) additively complete), which the sibling repo's own whitepaper explicitly states remains OPEN and is not attacked by this line of work. Proof authority: Lean kernel via the tracked proof-search loop (episode a6801189, problem_version 420dd077-4bed-4b31-835e-6f47617b3e40), a single Solve step, kernel_verified on the first attempt. Notably, problem_create's returned root_statement_hash (2328323a2b3bbeba5fa2318fbc84fd47675231f738edc38166e21687ced920ed) exactly matches the hash cited in the sibling repo's own source comment for the upstream google-deepmind/formal-conjectures statement -- strong evidence of byte-identical statement fidelity, hence statement_fidelity: canonical_statement_hash_match rather than adapted_with_review. Independently re-verified in THIS environment's own pinned toolchain rather than treated as evidence merely because the sibling repo (F:\\Github\\mnehmos.llm-driven-proof-search.environment\\ErdosProblems\\erdos-349\\proof\\Erdos349_exists_finset_sum_two_pow.lean, its own tracked episode 844e5846-fc4b-4651-b1dd-9e0735a643ce) already reports it kernel_verified there -- per this repo's evidence policy. training.eligibility: quarantined per the default-quarantine policy for open_problem_related packets pending real external review (same policy applied to frontier.erdos.erdos_399_cambie.v1). Second packet in the frontier/erdos lane.",
